\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{E}/c$
\end_inset

, and the space terms the 3d momentum
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Defined an anologous Force as 
\begin_inset Formula $dP^{i}/ds$
\end_inset

.
 The hint for the first component is that you can write Energy as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{E}=\mathbf{p.v}-L$
\end_inset

 [ASK: How does L not depend on time? Perhaps we could say that since the
 equation of motion is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\left(\frac{\partial L}{\partial\mathbf{v}}\right)=\frac{\partial L}{\partial\mathbf{r}}
\]

\end_inset

Since the Lagrangian has no explicit dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

, it implies, the momentum is constant.
 This implies the velocity is constant.
 Thus all terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 are constants (with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

).
 QED]
\end_layout

