\begin_layout Section*
16.
 Four-potential of a field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Added the interaction with the field in the action.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\int\left(-mcds-\frac{e}{c}A_{i}dx^{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You can break this into the lagrangian (just re-epxress 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}dx^{i}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A},\phi,d\mathbf{r},dt$
\end_inset

 and you get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L=-mc^{2}\sqrt{1-\frac{v^{2}}{c^{2}}}+\frac{e}{c}\mathbf{A.v}-e\phi
\]

\end_inset

The origin of this makes sense now! (remember you saw this first in sakurai?,
 the Hamiltonian perhaps)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{P}=\partial L/\partial\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to find the generalized momentum (we still use 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{p}$
\end_inset

 for epxressing the momentum of the free particle).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that in the lagrangian formalism, everything is 3D agian.
 The action varation gives the 4D anaologues.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Again, we can also express the energy/hamiltonian using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{H}=\mathbf{v.P}-L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
It needs a little `thinkable' manipulation to express the hamiltonian as
 a function of the generalized momentum.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
