\begin_layout Section*
23.
 The electromagnetic field tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The equations of motion can be derived using either the Lagrandian Formalism,
 or using the variation of action direclty.
 The latter's been done here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write down the action in the 4d notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Write 
\begin_inset Formula $ds=\sqrt{dx_{i}dx^{i}}$
\end_inset

 and apply 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 to all the terms, without holding 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 consant.
 Also substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $dx_{i}/ds=du_{i}$
\end_inset

 as you go.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Integrate by parts the two terms that don't have a 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta A_{i}$
\end_inset

 term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the part in the interal then, re-express 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta A_{i}=\frac{\partial A_{i}}{\partial x_{k}}\delta x_{k}
\]

\end_inset

and similarly 
\begin_inset Formula $dA_{i}$
\end_inset

 is re-expressed as partials.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now use the relation 
\begin_inset Formula $dx^{i}=u^{i}ds$
\end_inset

, and change indices suitably, so that you can take 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta x^{i}ds$
\end_inset

 common.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Now equating this to zero as usual, for the usual reasons, we get, (finally)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
mc\frac{du_{i}}{ds}=\frac{e}{c}\left(\frac{\partial A_{k}}{\partial x^{i}}-\frac{\partial A_{i}}{\partial x^{k}}\right)u^{k}
\]

\end_inset

and we define now for the first time
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{ik}=\frac{\partial A_{k}}{\partial x^{i}}-\frac{\partial A_{i}}{\partial x^{k}}
\]

\end_inset

the antisymmetric electromagnetic field tensor!
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
You can find 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ik}$
\end_inset

 in terms of field strengths by simply using 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}=(\phi,\mathbf{A})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
According to section 6, you can then also write 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{ik}=(\mathbf{E,\, H}),\, F^{ik}=(-\mathbf{E,\, H})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
<properties skipped> 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The next step is then to find the generalized momentum.
 That's simple as it comes from the other part (non-integral).
 We then do the old trick.
 Find 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta S/\delta x^{i}$
\end_inset

 and call it 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{i}$
\end_inset

 and get the relation required.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
